<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12045f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12045f">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12045f"> 45(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Chartrier / muniment room</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Aussi Pierre Le Roy fit-il construire un local sp&eacute;cialement am&eacute;nag&eacute; pour conserver les tr&eacute;sors litt&eacute;raires et les titres de propri&eacute;t&eacute; du Mont. Il est l&apos;architecte du <mark>Chartrier</mark>. / Le Chartrier se trouve &agrave; l&apos;angle nord-ouest de la Merveille; il est form&eacute; de trois petites salles superpos&eacute;es; la premi&egrave;re seule est vo&ucirc;t&eacute;e; le <font color="green">[22]</font> clo&icirc;tre, dans sa partie occidentale, communique avec le deuxi&egrave;me &eacute;tage de ce local un peu exigu. Il est construit d&apos;apr&egrave;s les r&egrave;gles de l&apos;architecture b&eacute;n&eacute;dictine et r&eacute;pond, presque trait pour trait, &agrave; la description du fameux chartrier de l&apos;abbaye de Th&eacute;l&egrave;me que Rabelais nous donne avec son habituelle faconde. Actuellement, le chartrier auquel les touristes n&apos;ont pas acc&egrave;s forme &agrave; l&apos;&eacute;tage sup&eacute;rieur, un petit mus&eacute;e o&ugrave; ont &eacute;t&eacute; r&eacute;unis quelques objets d&eacute;couverts au cours des travaux de r&eacute;fection. <br><font color="green">[Pierre Le Roy also built a room specially designed to hold the literary treasures and the property titles of the Mont. He is the architect of the Cartulary. The Cartulary is situated in the North-West conrner of the Merveille: it consists of the three small rooms on top of each other: the first alone is vaulted; the cloister, in its western part, leads unto the second floor of this rather small room. It is built according to the rules of Benedictine architecture and seems to be replica, trait for trait, of the description of the famous cartulary of the abbey of Th&eacute;l&egrave;me that Rabelais gives us with his usual eloquence. At the moment the cartulary that tourists do not have access to, forms a museum at the top floor where some objects are assembled that were discovered during the repair works.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 22-23</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Muniment room is one of the senses of the French word <i>chartrier</i> (cartulary). It can also designate the contents of this room: all of the charters, titles and deeds in a cathedral, monastery or castle. </mm> </dd></dl>
